SMOKERS, vapers, and boozers will soon have to pay more for their favorite addiction. Finance minister Tito Mboweni has revealed in the 2020 Budget Speech that e-cigarette users will now start paying tax. Mboweni announced that a can of 340ml beer or cider will cost an extra 8 cents, a 750ml bottle of wine will cost an extra 14 cents, a 750ml bottle of sparkling wine will increase by 61 cents and a bottle of 750 ml spirits, including whisky, gin or vodka, will rise by R2.89. He also made it clear that a packet of 20 cigarettes will cost an extra 74 cents and a 23-gram cigar will cost an extra R6.73. “I am again happy to report that there is no increase in the price of sorghum beer,” He added.       